args: Don't you worry. Our army is mighty,\nand will never be defeated. I promise.
(Even so, the enemy is the Imperial Army.\nI pray everyone is careful...)
...The Empire is coming for your village?!
I'm afraid so. They've demanded an\nexorbitant tax from our village, as well\nas those in the surrounding area.
We are all poor and simple people;\nwe can't possibly afford to pay.
Yet they have decreed that any who fail to\npay will meet a swift and terrible end.
It is a warning. By destroying one village,\nthey show all the others that the Empire\nis not to be trifled with.
What a horrible thing to do!
I'd never let the Empire get away\nwith something so cruel.
...How terrible to think that village was\nyour hometown of Hosse.
My apologies that you have ended up\nwatching over the children, Norwin.
It is our duty to ease the worries of all\nvillagers—including the children.
Well, still you have our gratitude.
(This is just like when Anasonne\nwas destroyed...)
(Back then, I read a book to the young\nlord and lady to soothe them.)
(But now I'd only be able to tell the poor\nchildren a tale of horror and woe.\nHow powerless I have become!)
{player_name}, let me fight.\nOr at least let me provide support\nif I can do nothing else.
I appreciate that, Norwin, but we need you\nfor something else—a specific task that\nONLY you can do.
You're the only one who can give courage\nto these children—so do what you must.

(That's right! Did I not write it myself in
one of my books? No matter how scared
I get, the courage to take a single step
will open the way forward!)

Gather round, children; I'm going to read
you a picture book! It will be full of thrills
and chills and maybe even a scare or two,
but in the end, all will be happy!
Your fear is just what the Empire wants!\nYou must learn to be brave instead.
Now, let us begin. The title of this tale is\n＂The Princess in the Wall.＂
Long ago, in a far away land, there was\na small house that was surrounded on all\nsides by a wall that stretched to the sky.
...And after the witch cast her spell,\nthe princess found herself trapped\nwithin a frightful patch of brambles!
＂Ungrateful girl!＂ cried the nasty witch.\n＂I shall rip you to pieces!＂
(Now the prince will come to save the day.\nIf only reality could be so kind!)
(I remember how Anasonne's young nobles\nsought to gain courage and strength from\nthe brave prince I wrote about.)
Norwin?! What about the prince?!\nIsn't he gonna come save the princess?!
(N-no...I can't possibly be hearing them.\nThey're gone. They died!)
＂No one is coming to save you!＂ cackled\nthe witch. And so she trapped the\nprincess and...and...
It's okay! The prince is gonna come!
(They're completely absorbed in the tale,\neven as the Empire knocks at their door.)
(By Ilia... THIS is the power of fantasy!)

(The young nobles of Anasonne were
happy and brave even as their land was
consumed by war, and all because they
became engrossed in my stories.)
(What is left for me if I do not\nbelieve in that power?!)
Suddenly, there was a mighty explosion\nthat tore a hole in the wall! And standing\nthere amidst the dust and rubble, was...
That's right! The prince appeared and\ncut the bramble patch into little pieces,\nfreeing the princess in the process!
Then they lived happily ever after.
And all was right in the world.
I confess I was unsure of how reading a\npicture book could help, but it somehow\nhelped me to forget our dire situation.
And speaking of that situation, it seems\nthe noises outside have stopped.
The battle is over. But who won...?
Okay, everyone! You can come out!
Then the Empire has been defeated?!
For now, yes. And everyone's okay.
It seems reality is not all suffering;\nthere can also be great joy in it.
